1:00:29 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/code/M54.12 200 in 849ms :: {"guidelines":[{"id":"0-II.A-locating-a-code-in-the-icd-10-cm","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Locating a Code in the ICD-10-CM","content":"To select a code in the classification that corresponds to a diagnosis or reason for visit documented in a medical record, first locate the term in the Alphabetic Index, then verify the code in the Tabular List. Read and be guided by instructional notations that appear in both the Alphabetic Index and the Tabular List. It is essential to use both the Alphabetic Index and Tabular List when locating and assigning a code.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","locating codes","alphabetic index","tabular list"]},{"id":"0-II.B-level-of-detail-in-coding","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.B","title":"Level of Detail in Coding","content":"Diagnosis codes are to be used and reported at their highest number of characters available. A three-character code is to be used only if it is not further subdivided. A code is invalid if it has not been coded to the full number of characters required for that code, including the 7th character, if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","specificity","code detail","7th character"]},{"id":"0-II.C-code-or-codes-from-a00-0-through-t88-9-z00-z99-8","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.C","title":"Code or Codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89","content":"The appropriate code or codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89 must be used to identify diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, complaints or other reason(s) for the encounter/visit. Codes from A00.0 through T88.9 describe symptoms, signs, abnormal test results, or other reasons for the encounter. Z codes represent reasons for encounters and may be used in either the inpatient or outpatient setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","code selection","Z codes"]},{"id":"0-II.D-signs-and-symptoms","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.D","title":"Signs and Symptoms","content":"Codes that describe symptoms and signs, as opposed to diagnoses, are acceptable for reporting purposes when a related definitive diagnosis has not been established (confirmed) by the provider. The condition that is chiefly responsible for the outpatient encounter should be sequenced first. Integral signs/symptoms should not be coded separately unless instructed otherwise.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","signs","symptoms","sequencing"]},{"id":"0-II.E-conditions-that-are-an-integral-part-of-a-diseas","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.E","title":"Conditions that are an Integral Part of a Disease Process","content":"Signs and symptoms that are associated routinely with a disease process should not be assigned as additional codes, unless otherwise instructed by the classification. Codes for signs/symptoms that are routinely associated with a disease (e.g., fever with bacterial pneumonia) should not be assigned separately.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","disease process","integral signs"]},{"id":"0-II.J-laterality","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.J","title":"Laterality","content":"Some ICD-10-CM codes indicate laterality, specifying whether the condition occurs on the left, right or is bilateral. If no bilateral code is provided and the condition is bilateral, assign separate codes for both the left and right side. If the side is not identified in the medical record, assign the code for the unspecified side. When a patient has a bilateral condition and each side is treated during separate encounters, assign the bilateral code for the condition still present on both sides.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","laterality","bilateral","left","right"]},{"id":"0-II.K-documentation-by-clinicians-other-than-the-patie","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.K","title":"Documentation by Clinicians Other than the Patient's Provider","content":"Code assignment is based on the documentation by the patient's provider (i.e., physician or other qualified healthcare practitioner legally accountable for establishing the patient's diagnosis). Codes may be assigned based on documentation by clinicians who are not the patient's provider only for codes for Body Mass Index (BMI), depth of non-pressure chronic ulcers, pressure ulcer stage, coma scale, and NIHSS codes.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","documentation","provider","BMI","clinician"]},{"id":"13-C13.a-site-and-laterality-musculoskeletal","chapter":13,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Musculoskeletal System and Connective Tissue","section":"C13.a","title":"Site and Laterality — Musculoskeletal","content":"Most of the codes within Chapter 13 have site and laterality designations. The site represents the bone, joint or the muscle involved. For some conditions where more than one bone, joint or muscle is usually involved, such as osteoarthritis, there is a 'multiple sites' code available. For categories where no multiple site code is provided and more than one bone, joint or muscle is involved, multiple codes should be used to indicate the different sites involved.","codeRangeStart":"M00","codeRangeEnd":"M99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["musculoskeletal","site","laterality","M00-M99","bone","joint","muscle"]},{"id":"0-IV.A-selection-of-first-listed-condition-outpatient","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Outpatient Coding and Reporting Guidelines","section":"IV.A","title":"Selection of First-Listed Condition (Outpatient)","content":"In the outpatient setting, the term 'first-listed diagnosis' is used in lieu of 'principal diagnosis.' The appropriate code(s) should be assigned to describe all diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, or complaints treated or managed. The condition chiefly responsible for services provided is the first-listed diagnosis. Codes for signs and symptoms may be reported in addition to a related definitive diagnosis when the sign or symptom is not routinely associated with that diagnosis.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["outpatient","first-listed","principal diagnosis","sequencing","signs","symptoms"]},{"id":"0-II.A-principal-diagnosis-inpatient-selection","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Principal Diagnosis — Inpatient Selection","content":"The condition established after study to be chiefly responsible for occasioning the admission of the patient to the hospital for care is the principal diagnosis. In the unusual instance when two or more diagnoses equally meet the criteria for principal diagnosis, any one may be selected as principal. If the original treatment plan is not carried out, the condition that caused the original admission should still be the principal diagnosis. Coding professionals should not hesitate to query the attending provider when documentation is ambiguous.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["inpatient","principal diagnosis","admission","sequencing","attending provider"]},{"id":"0-III-reporting-of-additional-diagnoses","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"III","title":"Reporting of Additional Diagnoses","content":"For reporting purposes the definition for 'other diagnoses' is interpreted as additional conditions that affect patient care in terms of requiring clinical evaluation, therapeutic treatment, diagnostic procedures, extended length of hospital stay, or increased nursing care and/or monitoring. Diagnoses that relate to an earlier episode which have no bearing on the current hospital stay are to be excluded. UHDDS definitions apply to inpatient encounters in acute care, short-term, long term care and psychiatric hospital setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["additional diagnoses","inpatient","UHDDS","reporting","clinical evaluation"]},{"id":"0-HCPCS.GENERAL-hcpcs-level-ii-scope-and-usage","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"HCPCS Level II Coding Guidelines","section":"HCPCS.GENERAL","title":"HCPCS Level II — Scope and Usage","content":"HCPCS Level II codes are alphanumeric codes (letter A-V followed by 4 digits) developed by CMS to describe items and services not covered by CPT codes. They cover ambulance services (A codes), durable medical equipment (E codes), procedures/professional services (G codes), covered drugs (J codes), temporary non-Medicare codes (K codes), dental (D codes), and other items. HCPCS Level II codes are required for billing to Medicare and Medicaid for items and services they describe. Always verify current-year active status before using.","codeRangeStart":"A0000","codeRangeEnd":"V5364","type":"HCPCS","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/healthcare-common-procedure-system","tags":["HCPCS","Level II","DME","ambulance","drugs","J codes","G codes","K codes"]}],"nlmInfo":{"code":"M54.12","description":"Radiculopathy, cervical region","source":"ICD-10-CM"}}
